<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-280-886  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 280 886.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 11 1989 n1163 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hack through the security labyrinth. (computer security systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bicknell, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are three main security options for users of IBM 4381MVS-based systems: RACF, from IBM, and ACF2 and Top Secret fromComputer Associates International Inc. For the VM operating systemthere is VMSecure from Systems Center.andP;  RACF and ACF2 are accesscontrol facility packages.andP;  With RACF the onus is on the user toexplicitly identify security areas.andP;  ACF2 protects systems bydefault.andP;  The software determines access by referring to a logoniddatabase.andP;  The logonid is a record or system identifier thatdefines a user's identity and privileges.andP;  VMSecure offers usersan open or closed system.andP;  Top Secret, RACF and ACF2 all have a C2security rating from the US government.andP;  IBM is trying to obtain ahigher B rating for RACF.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   RACF (Computer program) (usage)ACF2 (Computer program) (usage)Top Secret (Computer program) (usage)VMSecure (computer program) (usage)VM (Operating system) (access control)IBM 4381 (Mainframe computer) (computer programs)VM (Operating system) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Computer HackersComputer CrimesSecurity SoftwareAccess ControlsMVS (Computer system)ApplicationsTelephones.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>